  <h2 class="artist">Untitled 1</h2>
  <p class="artinfo"><strong>Media:</strong> Digital Chromogenic Print</p>
  <p class="artinfo"><strong>Date of Creation:</strong> 2002</p>
  <img src="/static/img/gc1.png" class="img-rounded" alt="Gregory Crewdson" width="70%"><br><br>
  <p class="description">
    This is one of Gregory Crewdson’s photographs that had been part of his twelve-part portfolio “Dream House” in 2002. The name of the portfolio alone expresses a hope for a perfect home - a traditional suburban scene with a manicured lawn and hedges. However, this image displays a scene far from perfect. The broken fence and the white shingled house in this wooded area place this scene in the suburbs, and at first glance, it appears as if this is the typical aftermath of a car crash - the driver collecting her belongings after an accident in a seemingly quiet neighborhood. It seems to be early morning, but oddly enough, the main source of light in this photograph is the overturned car itself, emitting an unnatural glow. The only other source of light comes from the windows of the house, signifying that there is activity in the house. Yet the road is still desolate, with only the assumed driver gathering her belongings. She seems to have driven toward the brighter foreground of the image, as suggested by the direction of the other car in this photograph. Perhaps, this direction the woman has taken suggests that she had attempted to drive from a darker, more mysterious past toward a more seemingly pleasant space, only to find herself stuck again, with no mode of transportation, in the dark. As the name “Dream House” suggests, perfection - in this case, an ideal home - is unattainable, only a dream.
  </p>
  
