  <h2 class="artist">Untitled 2</h2>
  <p class="artinfo"><strong>Media:</strong> Digital Chromogenic Print</p>
  <p class="artinfo"><strong>Date of Creation:</strong> 2002</p>
  <img src="/static/img/gc2.png" class="img-rounded" alt="Gregory Crewdson" width="70%"><br><br>
  <p class="description">
    This is an untitled digital chromogenic print from Gregory Crewdson’s 2004 “Beneath the Roses” exhibit in 2004. This image is, upon first glance, simply a car driving in the middle of a road at a quiet time of day. However, there is something eerily unsettling about this scene - the car is in fact not being driven on the desolate road: the door has been thrown open, the background is foggy and mysteriously unclear. The car is stopped past the traffic lights, and the door has been left open with no driver, giving off the sense that there must have been some sort of serious catalyst for the driver to have left the car in such a state. There seems to be a source of light from within the car shining past the door, again emphasizing that the car is stuck in its current state, neither fully stopped and parked nor fully ready to drive and serve its initial purpose. 
  </p>
  <p class="description">
    This car’s unnerving state is in stark contrast with its surroundings - the car is surrounded by a very geometrically, in a sense, perfectly, laid out neighborhood. The buildings are placed squarely against each other, the traffic light beams are exactly parallel to the ground, and the white paint on the road is drawn as precise rhombuses carefully placed beside each other. However, this perfect environment is rendered no longer perfect by the unheimlich, out-of-place car in the not-quite center of this image.
  </p>

