  <h2 class="artist">Untitled 3</h2>
  <p class="artinfo"><strong>Media:</strong> Digital Chromogenic Print</p>
  <p class="artinfo"><strong>Date of Creation:</strong> 2004</p>
  <img src="/static/img/gc3.png" class="img-rounded" alt="Gregory Crewdson" width="70%"><br><br>
  <p class="description">
    This photograph is an untitled production still from Gregory Crewdson’s “Beneath the Roses” exhibit in 2004. In this photograph, the viewer notices many images of doubleness, the duality of identity.The two people in this photograph are standing by the railroad in a seemingly suburban patch of land, with tall grass growing on either side of the railroad. The viewer’s eyes trace the railroad, attempting to find an origin, but are stopped when they see the particularly bright light shining on the railroad at the edge of the photograph, obscuring the railroad’s path. The two people in the image are on opposite sides of the railroad. It is noteworthy that the casually dressed male figure stands between two rails; this and his deliberating figure suggests that he is at crossroads, torn between two identities. The girl in the background  is equally casually dressed, but her demeanor seems to suggest a carefree spirit. We question how these two figures and their contrasting attitudes relate - perhaps they are two different reflections of one.
  </p>
